      "seed": 2089430859,
      "version": 205,
      "versionNonce": 775687368,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "there are different data structure as part of redis:\n1. strings\n2. hash\n3. sets\n4. sorted set\n5. list\n6. stream\n7. bloom filters\n8. GSI ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "there are different data structure as part of redis:\n1. strings\n2. hash\n3. sets\n4. sorted set\n5. list\n6. stream\n7. bloom filters\n8. GSI ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "iBVE5pFBltWfeihwIcLuo",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 349.71834273624063,
      "y": -8786.394833037073,
      "width": 996.87939453125,
      "height": 175,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bHw",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 891254795,
      "version": 462,
      "versionNonce": 1827537848,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Redis replication: data is stored in another node for retention, but the replication lag may be there\n\nSharding: Data is stored in hash slots around 2^14. The slots are shared to the client when it makes\na first call, then the specific node can be used for getting the data for any value. \nDuring rebalancing this hash slot map is updated.\n\nPerformance: Upto 100k writes per second.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Redis replication: data is stored in another node for retention, but the replication lag may be there\n\nSharding: Data is stored in hash slots around 2^14. The slots are shared to the client when it makes\na first call, then the specific node can be used for getting the data for any value. \nDuring rebalancing this hash slot map is updated.\n\nPerformance: Upto 100k writes per second.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "OXgQrEEEMCys9wntAnP1Y",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -330.90810379216623,
      "y": -8524.39234129426,
      "width": 1744.47900390625,
      "height": 700,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bHy",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 827650859,
      "version": 1632,
      "versionNonce": 598684616,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Capabilities:\n\n1. Redis as cache: key-value store. \n    1. TTL of keys, the keys gets autodeleted. Internally uses both lazily and proactive deletion of keys.\n\n2. Redis as distributed lock:\n   1. Assigns a key with lock value and expiry timestamp\n   2. the other node comes and acquire it. It also goes on executing the transaction. \n[not sure on this.]\n\n3. redis for leaderboards:\n   1. store the playerId and score in sorted set\n   2. get the top x players from that sorted set. \n\n4. rate limiting:\n  1. store the timestamp in the sorted set, remove the older values depending on current time stamp. Get the size of sorted set to allow or not. This is sliding window appraoch.\n  2. keep a counter with expiry, update it with each request. If it goes beyond than required, rate limit the coming request. Else then allow. Post expiry again create new counter.\n\n5. proximity search:\n  1. find the nearest (long,lat) to a specific location. \n\n6. event streaming:\n  1. it also provides pub-sub functionality. This one is fast as there is no data retention and everything runs on memory.\n  2. it has concepts of channels(topics in kafka) and consumer groups. Across the group ensuring single delivery of message. \n[not sure why it is used as compared to kafka streaming.]\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Capabilities:\n\n1. Redis as cache: key-value store. \n    1. TTL of keys, the keys gets autodeleted. Internally uses both lazily and proactive deletion of keys.\n\n2. Redis as distributed lock:\n   1. Assigns a key with lock value and expiry timestamp\n   2. the other node comes and acquire it. It also goes on executing the transaction. \n[not sure on this.]\n\n3. redis for leaderboards:\n   1. store the playerId and score in sorted set\n   2. get the top x players from that sorted set. \n\n4. rate limiting:\n  1. store the timestamp in the sorted set, remove the older values depending on current time stamp. Get the size of sorted set to allow or not. This is sliding window appraoch.\n  2. keep a counter with expiry, update it with each request. If it goes beyond than required, rate limit the coming request. Else then allow. Post expiry again create new counter.\n\n5. proximity search:\n  1. find the nearest (long,lat) to a specific location. \n\n6. event streaming:\n  1. it also provides pub-sub functionality. This one is fast as there is no data retention and everything runs on memory.\n  2. it has concepts of channels(topics in kafka) and consumer groups. Across the group ensuring single delivery of message. \n[not sure why it is used as compared to kafka streaming.]\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "5eQ3Z-tz2y_c_w3dbmtHr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -314.3115745543996,
      "y": -7794.151727980256,
      "width": 1532.2587890625,
      "height": 725,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bHz",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1284497579,
      "version": 1294,
      "versionNonce": 417647800,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Data structures in deep:\n\n1. strings:\n stores the values of string. The most basic ones. \n SET key value\n SET key value ex 2 [has expiry after 2 seconds]\n Only during increment, add or decrement calls the the expiry time remains same, or make call in a way that it remains same with extra params, else the expiry\n time will be gone. \n 5. stores jsob blob also as JSONB object (not sure)\n\n\n2. queue/lists:\n  1. similar to doubly linked list\n  2. provides functionality of both queue and stack.\n  3. can be used in which the tasks are being added, and pulled from background workers to \nrun the task. \n  \n\n3. hashes:\n  1. modelling objects and all in redis\n  2. serialization and deserialization not needed as in case of string based hash\n\n4. sets:\n  1. uses hashtable, simply keep the values\n  2. eviction policy with timestamp can be there\n\n5. sorted set\n  1. uniqueness ordering, fast range queries and ranking\n  2. used in leaderboard",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Data structures in deep:\n\n1. strings:\n stores the values of string. The most basic ones. \n SET key value\n SET key value ex 2 [has expiry after 2 seconds]\n Only during increment, add or decrement calls the the expiry time remains same, or make call in a way that it remains same with extra params, else the expiry\n time will be gone. \n 5. stores jsob blob also as JSONB object (not sure)\n\n\n2. queue/lists:\n  1. similar to doubly linked list\n  2. provides functionality of both queue and stack.\n  3. can be used in which the tasks are being added, and pulled from background workers to \nrun the task. \n  \n\n3. hashes:\n  1. modelling objects and all in redis\n  2. serialization and deserialization not needed as in case of string based hash\n\n4. sets:\n  1. uses hashtable, simply keep the values\n  2. eviction policy with timestamp can be there\n\n5. sorted set\n  1. uniqueness ordering, fast range queries and ranking\n  2. used in leaderboard",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ft-w1IeqtH9kZhsoTpF5u",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -324.1105554259003,
      "y": -7030.502865118433,
      "width": 520.57958984375,
      "height": 75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bI0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1408059500,
      "version": 143,
      "versionNonce": 1847950024,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "6. streaming:\n  1. redis pub-sub is lightweight, not durable and fast\n  2. kafka: durable, in-disk and latency is higher. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "6. streaming:\n  1. redis pub-sub is lightweight, not durable and fast\n  2. kafka: durable, in-disk and latency is higher. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "L2t9ALRr0u13Y-4TmyfmR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 645.88387282752,
      "y": -7020.820525090498,
      "width": 609.879638671875,
      "height": 125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bI1",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1975539540,
      "version": 239,
      "versionNonce": 219837880,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Nodes talk to each other via custom TCP protocol.\nsharding in redis is client based, the hash slots are \nnot used on the server side. The hash slots are shared in the\nfirst call to redis.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Nodes talk to each other via custom TCP protocol.\nsharding in redis is client based, the hash slots are \nnot used on the server side. The hash slots are shared in the\nfirst call to redis.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "gqMcmkhPMtNK9oGopv5sn",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 439.033881321573,
      "y": -6828.053937261551,
      "width": 709.9595336914062,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bI2",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 379649876,
      "version": 357,
      "versionNonce": 1077600712,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772711525068,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. hot key resolution:\n   1. add keys on multiple nodes, can be done only if the key values\ncan be decomposed and recomposed. \n   2. the redis does not shard internally the client has to shard the key\nto ensure that key does not remain hot. \n   3. the redis server is kept simple, most complexity is handled by client.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. hot key resolution:\n   1. add keys on multiple nodes, can be done only if the key values\ncan be decomposed and recomposed. \n   2. the redis does not shard internally the client has to shard the key\nto ensure that key does not remain hot. \n   3. the redis server is kept simple, most complexity is handled by client.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "gZ2QsvhJ9eME1IyFllumM",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 581.9673800935185,
