      "locked": false,
      "text": "4. DB indexing:\n\nmutliple indexes wrt DB for SQL like hash index, b trees, geospatial, entire doc check.(like elastic search)\n\ncomposite index can also be there. \n\n5. caching:\n\nfrequent reads: redis. TTL can be there to ensure we don't send stale data to our clients.\nhandling cache failures: DB might be overloaded\n   - small in process cache can help like feature flag systems.\n\n6. sharding:\n\ndifferent ways to do : hash based, range based. \nMostly can come handy if very high number of writes, share the assumption in interview when talking.\n\nconsistent hashing: handles the rebalancing effectively.\n\n7. CAP theorm\nDecision in consistency and availability.\nWe usually go with eventual consistency in systems.\n\nsome numbers to know: memory 1 nanosecond, ssd 1 microsecond.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "4. DB indexing:\n\nmutliple indexes wrt DB for SQL like hash index, b trees, geospatial, entire doc check.(like elastic search)\n\ncomposite index can also be there. \n\n5. caching:\n\nfrequent reads: redis. TTL can be there to ensure we don't send stale data to our clients.\nhandling cache failures: DB might be overloaded\n   - small in process cache can help like feature flag systems.\n\n6. sharding:\n\ndifferent ways to do : hash based, range based. \nMostly can come handy if very high number of writes, share the assumption in interview when talking.\n\nconsistent hashing: handles the rebalancing effectively.\n\n7. CAP theorm\nDecision in consistency and availability.\nWe usually go with eventual consistency in systems.\n\nsome numbers to know: memory 1 nanosecond, ssd 1 microsecond.\n",
